      "post_id" : 51656488,
      "comment_id" : 96414367,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I was trying it out. It&#39;s exactly like what it was stated in the link above. Change the build -&gt; finalName attribute value to your context path. The resulting war file will then be using the context path as the filename, which will then be used by tomcat to serve as the context path."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 5619551,
        "reputation" : 765,
        "user_id" : 4449859,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9152ea82e7edf6f5c167dab1659c682?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "abdel",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4449859/abdel"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1554460494,
      "post_id" : 51656488,
      "comment_id" : 97770044,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "the only way i can think of for deploying as war in external tomcat is to ensure the war name matches the context you are after. so for example, if you want the context to be &#39;/xyzwebapp&#39; then your war must be named xyzwebapp.war. to achieve this, you can add the following to the &lt;build&gt; element in your pom.xml :         &lt;finalName&gt;xyzwebapp&lt;/finalName&gt;."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5619551,
      "reputation" : 765,
      "user_id" : 4449859,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9152ea82e7edf6f5c167dab1659c682?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
